Manoj Kumar C V • Aug 2018
Thrissur, India  •  692 contributions
Vadakkunnathan temple is an old Hindu temple in Thrissur Kerala. The main diety is lord Shiva. There are a number of other dieties like parvathi, ganesa, Krishna, ayyappa, sankaranarayana etc. The order in which it is to be visited is very special. There is a goshala. Kuthambalam is also famous. It is where temple arts are performed. Thrissur Pooram is held in the premises of this temple. The main participans are Paramekkavu Bhagavathi temple and Thiruvambadi Sreekrishna Temple. There at least 15 other participating temples. This festival is known for largest participation, elephants, fireworks etc. The temple is of Archaeological importance and that aspect is managed by Archaeological Survey of India. There are centuries old mural paintings also.

indiamirrorholidays1 • Apr 2018
Kochi (Cochin), India  •  121 contributions
Vadakkumnathan Temple history dates back to over 1,000 years. The history of the temple is connected with the birth of the great Kerala scholar, Guru Adi Shankaracharya. Shankara was born to the Shivaguru - Aryamba couple of Kalady, in answer to their prayers to God Vadakkunnathan. According to legends, Lord Shiva appeared to both husband and wife in their dream. He offered them a choice that they could have either an ordinary son who would live a long life or an extraordinary son who would die early. The couple chose the second option. They named the son Adi Shankara, in honour of Shiva. It is said that Adi Shankara attained Videha Mukti (Freedom from embodiment) in Vadakkunnathan temple.

Vadakkunnathan Temple

Vadakkumnathan Temple history dates back to over 1,000 years. The history of the temple is connected with the birth of the great Kerala scholar, Guru Adi Shankaracharya. Shankara was born to the Shivaguru - Aryamba couple of Kalady, in answer to their prayers to God Vadakkunnathan. According to legends, Lord Shiva appeared to both husband and wife in their dream. He offered them a choice that they could have either an ordinary son who would live a long life or an extraordinary son who would die early. The couple chose the second option. They named the son Adi Shankara, in honour of Shiva. It is said that Adi Shankara attained Videha Mukti (Freedom from embodiment) in Vadakkunnathan temple.

Hi i want to do 40 days mandala puja in this temple ,i want to know the procedure and where to stay in the night i mean which temple allows me to sleep and in which temple pond i can take bath and do puja kindly tell i am from andhra dont know any thing about kerala culture, iwant to stay in the temple premises 40 days
DrValliappan
Coimbatore, India6,687 contributions
Temple does not allow stay within premises. Even cemented open area outside (car park) is also locked during night. Pond is not for bath as water for pooja is taken from there. There are basic lodges just by the side of the lane of temple along with small restaurants. Comfortable hotel means Kerala Tourism Development Corporation (KTDC) about 20 KM from temple. Name of place is Changanassery. By the way Mandala Pooja is 48 days and not 40. Hope this info helps.
